<subSubSection id="2931610737FAD3BA5D262B3B483057EA" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph id="8638A2DA586A5EF7B657757EA3E6F5B7" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="66F410A3029BC136B8244796C4786C1B" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName id="B8EF2B77B8A48804C6C567D49C57C2BA" class="Equisetopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Coccoloba" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Coccoloba uvifera" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="uvifera">
<emphasis id="615F7B1CB0FDCEB45740A7C6B9A70266" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Coccoloba uvifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to coastal beaches throughout tropical America and the Caribbean. It is wind- and salt-tolerant and very often planted in ornamental plantations in warm-temperate and subtropical areas across the world, especially near the coast. It is very commonly grown in the Canary Islands as well. Fruits (sea grapes) are produced abundantly and relatively easily germinate. However, since ornamental plantings usually are found in urban habitats, regeneration is rarely observed. When planted in more natural suitable habitats, 
<taxonomicName id="5AD4A0173BCA06C136919918F539DC8C" authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. uvifera" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="uvifera">
<emphasis id="63DF65241F0CCE05139949AA57E67298" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">C. uvifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
readily naturalises and is sometimes considered an environmental weed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F6B522853B72F3457D91676F143A49D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
Despite being very commonly planted, the species had not been recorded so far as an escape in the Canary Islands until recently, when it was observed to copiously regenerate in two localities in La Palma (
<bibRefCitation id="F0F7E5236A9A546AC1C5337BDFF4AA63" author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509388" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2016. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species. Collectanea Botanica 35" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species" volume="35" year="2016">Otto and Verloove 2016</bibRefCitation>
). In December 2019, a single self-sown shrub (flowering and fruiting) was observed growing on a sea cliff below a coastal path in Puerto de Santiago (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9CCCC1BDF716573F47E3F58A55819748" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F6510143" captionText="Figure 3. Coccoloba uvifera, flowering and fruiting in Santiago del Teide (Puerto de Santiago), December 2019." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494342" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">3</figureCitation>
). It obviously escaped from a nearby plantation. For a number of reasons, a future local naturalisation in the Canary Islands is not unlikely: there is a climatic match, numerous suitable habitats and plenty of seed sources.
</paragraph>
